{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521692"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:36:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:36:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13693"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13693"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.03,0.02,0.84,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6301"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58150"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6301"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43609"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9160"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44550"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58150"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of colicky central abdominal pain and vomiting. She has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes and had an appendicectomy three years ago. She takes perindopril and metformin. She is a non-smoker and drinks several glasses of wine at weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 135/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She is obese with a BMI of 34 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E and this limits the abdominal examination. There are no abnormal findings apart from increased bowel sounds. A CT scan is performed (Images 1 - 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Small bowel adhesive obstruction","Enterocutaneous fistula","Infected rectus sheath haematoma","Incarcerated paraumbilical hernia","Omphalitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms could be explained by a number of conditions including intestinal obstruction, cholecystitis and pancreatitis - although colicky abdominal pain is less likely in the latter two.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn accurate abdominal examination can often be a challenge in the obese patient, as it proved to be here. CT imaging is being used with increasing frequency in the assessment of patients with the acute abdomen and in this case has provided the diagnosis. A paraumbilical hernia is clearly visible and the pocket of gas within it confirms a loop of small bowel. Thus this patient has an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincarcerated paraumbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E causing small bowel obstruction. Paraumbilical hernias occur more commonly in obese women and are a frequent cause of small bowel obstruction. More typically the presence of a tender, irreducible mass at the site of the hernia will be diagnostic. Many things, including hernias and areas of tenderness, can be hidden by layers of subcutaneous fat.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel adhesive obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E can present with abdominal pain, vomiting, and dilated bowel on X-ray. Adhesions are the most common cause of small bowel obstruction overall. The patient has had previous abdominal surgery and the diagnosis of adhesive-obstruction must always be considered - and can occur many years after the surgical procedure, however in this case this is not consistent with the CT scan results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eenterocutaneous fistula\u003C/strong\u003E is an abnormal connection between the small intestine and the skin. While it can cause abdominal pain and discharge, it typically doesn\u0027t present with acute small bowel obstruction as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einfected rectus sheath haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute abdominal pain and a tender mass in the abdominal wall. While it can occur in patients on anticoagulation or after trauma, it would not cause bowel obstruction as seen on the CT scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmphalitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an infection of the umbilicus and surrounding tissues, most commonly seen in newborns. In adults, it can occur with poor hygiene but would present with localised inflammation and discharge rather than bowel obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Paraumbilical hernias are a common cause of small bowel obstruction, especially in obese women.","CT abdomen can identify the transition point and confirm the diagnosis of an incarcerated hernia.","Obesity can make physical examination challenging, necessitating imaging for diagnosis."],"references":["Nachiappin S, Mortimer R, Howlett DC. Computed tomography in the assessment of the acute abdomen. RCS Bull. 2018; 296-300. Available at: https://appliedradiology.com/articles/computed-tomography-of-the-acute-abdomen"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43609"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13693"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20654"},{"type":"media","id":"20655"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20654"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EIv0Sjoi7r6MmLufaoE7gSNa1jTzQh.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EIv0Sjoi7r6MmLufaoE7gSNa1jTzQh.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":800}},{"type":"media","id":"20655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20655"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c52vUhRPpdxSfuhYRj6HmsBMKXLdV.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c52vUhRPpdxSfuhYRj6HmsBMKXLdV.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":953}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43609"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-29T15:35:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T15:46:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6301"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58150"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medici